<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05009b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05009b">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05009b"> 9(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> SP thrashes cleric</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The holy master Patrick was one who taught clearly that charity was not a mere matter of feeling, but a duty, as we see from the punishments he inflicted on those who sinned against this virtue. An instance of this is recorded in the case of the cure of a blind man, who hearing that the Saint was passing, ran to meet him in the hope of receiving his sight; and as he hurried along, staggering and falling, as he had no one to guide him, <mark>one of the clerics</mark> in the Saint&apos;s company burst out laughing, and made sport of the poor man. <mark>St. Patrick</mark> was filled with indignation, and as a warning to those around him &hellip; rebuked the scoffer, and <mark>chastised him with his own hand</mark> <small> William Bullen Morris, <a name="WBML" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WBML"><cite title="source">The Life of Saint Patrick Apostle of Ireland</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1890) 248</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02013a" href="c02all.htm#c02013a">VI.C.02:013(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
